.SH "NAME"
Win32::Event \- Use Win32 event objects from Perl
.SH "VERSION"
.IX Header "VERSION"
This document describes version 1.07 of Win32::Event, released April 16, 2008 as part of Win32\-IPC version 1.07.
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&        use Win32::Event;
\&
\&        $event = Win32::Event\->new($manual,$initial,$name);
\&        $event\->wait();
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module allows access to the Win32 event objects.  The \f(CW\*(C`wait\*(C'\fR
method and \f(CW\*(C`wait_all\*(C'\fR & \f(CW\*(C`wait_any\*(C'\fR functions are inherited from the
Win32::IPC module.
.Sh "Methods"
.IX Subsection "Methods"
.ie n .IP "$event = Win32::Event\->new([$manual, [$initial, [$name]]])" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$event\fR = Win32::Event\->new([$manual, [$initial, [$name]]])" 4
.IX Item "$event = Win32::Event->new([$manual, [$initial, [$name]]])"
Constructor for a new event object.  If \f(CW$manual\fR is true, you must
manually reset the event after it is signalled (the default is false).
If \f(CW$initial\fR is true, the initial state of the object is signalled
(default false).  If \f(CW$name\fR is omitted or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR, creates an
unnamed event object.
.Sp
If \f(CW$name\fR signifies an existing event object, then \f(CW$manual\fR and
\&\f(CW$initial\fR are ignored and the object is opened.  If this happens,
\&\f(CW$^E\fR will be set to 183 (\s-1ERROR_ALREADY_EXISTS\s0).
.ie n .IP "$event = Win32::Event\->open($name)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$event\fR = Win32::Event\->open($name)" 4
.IX Item "$event = Win32::Event->open($name)"
Constructor for opening an existing event object.
.ie n .IP "$event\->pulse" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$event\fR\->pulse" 4
.IX Item "$event->pulse"
\&\fBMicrosoft has stated this function is unreliable and should be
avoided.\fR Consult Microsoft's documentation for \f(CW\*(C`PulseEvent\*(C'\fR for
details.
.Sp
Signal the \f(CW$event\fR and then immediately reset it.  If \f(CW$event\fR is a
manual-reset event, releases all threads currently blocking on it.  If
it's an auto-reset event, releases just one thread.
.Sp
If no threads are waiting, just resets the event.
.Sp
It returns a true value if successful, or zero on failure
(additional error information can be found in \f(CW$^E\fR).
.ie n .IP "$event\->reset" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$event\fR\->reset" 4
.IX Item "$event->reset"
Reset the \f(CW$event\fR to nonsignalled.  It returns a true value if
successful, or zero on failure (additional error information can be
found in \f(CW$^E\fR).
.ie n .IP "$event\->set" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$event\fR\->set" 4
.IX Item "$event->set"
Set the \f(CW$event\fR to signalled.  It returns a true value if
successful, or zero on failure (additional error information can be
found in \f(CW$^E\fR).
.ie n .IP "$event\->wait([$timeout])" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$event\fR\->wait([$timeout])" 4
.IX Item "$event->wait([$timeout])"
Wait for \f(CW$event\fR to be signalled.  See Win32::IPC.
.SH "DIAGNOSTICS"
.IX Header "DIAGNOSTICS"
None.
.SH "CONFIGURATION AND ENVIRONMENT"
.IX Header "CONFIGURATION AND ENVIRONMENT"
Win32::Event requires no configuration files or environment variables.
.PP
It runs under 32\-bit or 64\-bit Microsoft Windows, either natively or
under Cygwin.
